Aper's high estimato of Caesar’s oratorical abilities is fully shared by Quint. X 1, 114 C. vero Caesar siforo tantum vacasset non alius ex nostris contra Ciceronem nominaretur. Tanta in 60 vis est, id acumen, ea concitatio, ut illum eodem animo dixisse quo 'bellavit appareat. Cf. also Tac. Ann. XIII 3 dictator Caesar summis oratoribus aemulus Suet. Caes. 55 quoting from a letter of Cicero: Quid? oratorum quem huic antepones eorum qui nihil aliud eqerunt. For other eulogies of Caesar's eloquence, see the references in Teuffel ἓ 195, 1., 111 Brut. 68, 239, Cicero pretends to account for Pompey's oratorical deficiencies on similar grounds ε vir ad omnia summa natus, maiorem dicendi gloriam habuisset, nisi eum maioris gloriae cupiditas ad bellicas laudes abstraxisset. —Brutum philosophiae suae relinquamus etc. ε This criticism is again in close agreement with Quintilian,who, while predicating ‘gravitas' of Brutus’ speeches (XII 10,10 cf. also Caesar's judg- ment cited below), significantly excludes their author from his list of orators, relegating him to the philosophers. Cf. 'X 1, 124 Egre- gius vero multoque quam in orationibus praestantior Brutus suf- fecit ponderi rerum : scias eum sentire quae dicit. Cicero, as well known, dedicated to him his Tusculan Disput., the de finibus and the de natura deorum and Plut.
